trait_descriptions.Honesty-Humility: Tendency toward sincerity, fairness, modesty, and avoidance of greed or exploitation
trait_descriptions.Emotionality: Tendency to experience anxiety, fear, emotional dependence, and empathetic sentimentality
trait_descriptions.Extraversion: Tendency toward social self-esteem, social boldness, sociability, and liveliness in expressions
trait_descriptions.Agreeableness: Tendency toward forgiveness, gentleness, flexibility, patience, and interpersonal trust
trait_descriptions.Conscientiousness: Tendency toward organization, diligence, perfectionism, and prudent deliberation
trait_descriptions.Openness: Tendency toward aesthetic appreciation, intellectual curiosity, creativity, and unconventionality
trait_descriptions.Dominance: Tendency toward assertiveness, leadership, control-seeking, and interpersonal influence
trait_descriptions.Vigilance: Tendency toward cautiousness, skepticism, wariness of intentions, and threat detection
trait_descriptions.Self-Transcendence: Tendency toward spirituality, sense of interconnectedness, altruism, and universal values
trait_descriptions.Abstract Orientation: Tendency to prefer conceptual ideas, theoretical possibilities, and intangible concepts
trait_descriptions.Value Orientation: Tendency to prioritize personal values, emotions, and moral principles in decision-making
trait_descriptions.Flexibility: Tendency toward adaptability, spontaneity, comfort with ambiguity, and openness to change

facet_descriptions.Modesty: A tendency to be humble and unassuming rather than entitled or self-important
facet_descriptions.Anxiety: A tendency to worry, be nervous, and experience heightened concerns about potential problems
facet_descriptions.Organization: A tendency to seek order, structure, and neatness in one's environment and activities
facet_descriptions.Trust: A tendency to believe that others are generally well-intentioned and trustworthy
facet_descriptions.Sincerity: A tendency to be genuine in interpersonal relations, avoiding manipulation or deception
facet_descriptions.Fairness: A tendency to avoid fraud and corruption, treating others equally and justly
facet_descriptions.Greed Avoidance: A tendency to be disinterested in displays of wealth, luxury, and social status
facet_descriptions.Fearfulness: A tendency to experience fear in response to potential physical dangers or threats
facet_descriptions.Dependence: A tendency to seek emotional support and validation from others
facet_descriptions.Sentimentality: A tendency to form strong emotional bonds and feel empathy toward others
facet_descriptions.Social Self-Esteem: A tendency to maintain positive self-worth and confidence in social contexts
facet_descriptions.Social Boldness: A tendency to feel comfortable and assertive in diverse social situations
facet_descriptions.Sociability: A tendency to seek out and enjoy social gatherings and interactions with others
facet_descriptions.Liveliness: A tendency to display enthusiasm, energy, and optimism in social settings
facet_descriptions.Forgiveness: A tendency to restore trust and release negative emotions toward those who have caused hurt
facet_descriptions.Gentleness: A tendency to be mild, cooperative, and lenient in dealings with others
facet_descriptions.Patience: A tendency to remain calm and tolerant when faced with frustrating people or situations
facet_descriptions.Diligence: A tendency to work hard, persist through challenges, and be thorough in tasks
facet_descriptions.Perfectionism: A tendency to be meticulous, precise, and concerned with details and standards
facet_descriptions.Prudence: A tendency to deliberate carefully, inhibit impulses, and consider consequences
facet_descriptions.Aesthetic Appreciation: A tendency to notice, value, and respond to beauty in art, nature, and design
facet_descriptions.Inquisitiveness: A tendency to seek knowledge, explore ideas, and ask questions about the world
facet_descriptions.Creativity: A tendency to generate novel ideas, think divergently, and explore unconventional solutions
facet_descriptions.Unconventionality: A tendency to accept the unusual, challenge traditions, and embrace non-conformity
facet_descriptions.Assertiveness: A tendency to lead, influence others, and speak up with confidence and conviction
facet_descriptions.Leadership: A tendency to take charge, direct group activities, and organize collective efforts
facet_descriptions.Control: A tendency to exert influence over situations, decisions, and people's behavior
facet_descriptions.Self-Confidence: A tendency to feel assured in one's abilities, judgments, and decisions
facet_descriptions.Suspicion: A tendency to be wary and doubtful of others' intentions and motives
facet_descriptions.Skepticism: A tendency to question claims and not easily accept statements without evidence
facet_descriptions.Wariness: A tendency to be cautious, vigilant, and alert to potential threats or problems
facet_descriptions.Distrust: A tendency to doubt others' reliability, honesty, or goodwill in interactions
facet_descriptions.Spirituality: A tendency to believe in transcendent realities, mystical experiences, or deeper meaning
facet_descriptions.Universality: A tendency to perceive fundamental connections among all living beings and nature
facet_descriptions.Altruism: A tendency to help others selflessly without expectation of personal benefit or reward
facet_descriptions.Unity: A tendency to experience harmony with the universe, nature, or a higher power
facet_descriptions.Conceptual Thinking: A tendency to work with abstract ideas, theoretical concepts, and mental models
facet_descriptions.Imagination: A tendency to envision possibilities beyond immediate reality and existing constraints
facet_descriptions.Idea-Focus: A tendency to be driven by conceptual insights rather than concrete practical details
facet_descriptions.Theoretical: A tendency to understand the world through principles, frameworks, and abstract reasoning
facet_descriptions.Empathy: A tendency to understand, share, and respond appropriately to others' emotional states
facet_descriptions.Moral Focus: A tendency to be guided by ethical principles and values in decision-making processes
facet_descriptions.Personal Values: A tendency to prioritize subjective values and principles over objective criteria
facet_descriptions.Emotional Reasoning: A tendency to incorporate feelings and subjective experience into judgment and decisions
facet_descriptions.Adaptability: A tendency to adjust readily and effectively to new or changed circumstances
facet_descriptions.Spontaneity: A tendency to act on impulse and respond to situations without extensive planning
facet_descriptions.Tolerance for Ambiguity: A tendency to be comfortable with uncertainty, complexity, and unclear situations
facet_descriptions.Openness to Change: A tendency to welcome new experiences, transitions, and alterations to routines

Modesty.notes: Strong negative correlation; modest individuals lack self-assuredness (Lee & Ashton, 2004)

Anxiety.notes: Anxiety creates hypervigilance; threat-detection systems are heightened (Bar-Haim et al., 2007)

Organization.notes: Organization reduces uncertainty tolerance; structured environments dislike ambiguity (Furnham & Ribchester, 1995)

Trust.notes: Direct conceptual opposites; trust and suspicion are mutually exclusive (Rotter, 1980)

Sincerity.notes: Authentic self-expression enhances social confidence (Wood et al., 2008)

Aesthetic Appreciation.notes: Beauty appreciation correlates with transcendent experiences (Huber & MacDonald, 2012)

Organization.notes: Organization serves anxiety regulation; structure controls worry (Kashdan et al., 2008)

Social Boldness.notes: Social confidence opposes fear responses (Schmidt & Fox, 2002)

Inquisitiveness.notes: Mild negative; perfectionism can inhibit exploration (Stoeber et al., 2018)

Altruism.notes: Helping behavior strongly linked to empathetic response (Batson et al., 1991)

Fairness.notes: Fair treatment correlates with cooperative behavior (Leung & Bond, 2004)

Forgiveness.notes: Forgiveness rebuilds and requires trust (Worthington et al., 2006)

Social Boldness.notes: Social confidence enables leadership emergence (Judge et al., 2002)

Diligence.notes: Work persistence requires organizational systems (Roberts et al., 2014)

Gentleness.notes: Cooperative behavior aligns with ethical principles (Roccas et al., 2002)

Greed Avoidance.notes: Material disinterest facilitates selfless giving (Lee et al., 2015)

Perfectionism.notes: Perfectionism strongly predicts anxiety (Egan et al., 2011)

Wariness.notes: Cautious vigilance and interpersonal distrust co-occur (Evans & Revelle, 2008)
